It's big, no?

03:20.263 --> 03:21.788
Ever since I entered physics,

03:22.161 --> 03:24.762
people have been talking about
this machine.

03:24.763 --> 03:27.430
The Large Hadron Collider,

03:27.431 --> 03:30.094
the biggest machine
ever built by human beings,

03:30.095 --> 03:32.562
is finally going to turn on.

03:32.563 --> 03:36.662
And after many, many years

03:36.663 --> 03:39.029
of waiting and theorizing

03:39.030 --> 03:40.828
about how matter got created

03:40.829 --> 03:43.695
and about what
the deep fundamental theory

03:43.696 --> 03:45.396
of nature is...

03:45.397 --> 03:49.028
all those theories
are finally going to be tested,

03:49.029 --> 03:50.863
and we're gonna know something.

03:50.864 --> 03:52.863
And we don't know
what it's gonna be now,

03:52.865 --> 03:54.230
but we will know,

03:54.231 --> 03:55.915
and it's gonna change
everything.

03:58.162 --> 04:01.764
And if the LHC
sees new particles,

04:01.765 --> 04:04.031
we're on the right track.

04:04.032 --> 04:07.898
And if it doesn't, not
only have we missed something,

04:07.899 --> 04:13.665
but we may not ever know
how to proceed.

04:14.664 --> 04:16.562
We are at a fork in the road,

04:16.563 --> 04:20.264
and it's either going to be
a golden era...

04:20.265 --> 04:21.930
Oh!

04:21.930 --> 04:24.864
Or it's going to be quite stark.

04:24.865 --> 04:29.331
And I've never heard of
a moment like this in history,

04:29.332 --> 04:34.197
where an entire field
is hinging on a single event.

04:34.198 --> 04:35.498
