04:38.399 --> 04:41.865
- So, look, I have suggested
to be on this side

04:41.866 --> 04:44.830
because this big wheel
is quite spectacular.

04:44.831 --> 04:47.332
Yeah, yeah.

04:47.333 --> 04:48.730
More than ever,

04:48.731 --> 04:50.565
this will require
the collaboration

04:50.566 --> 04:52.598
between the theory
and experimentalists,

04:52.599 --> 04:53.879
so it would be
a very nice period

04:54.065 --> 04:55.998
where we work together and,
uh...

04:55.999 --> 04:59.397
- Well, it's fun to finally
interact with experimentalists.

04:59.398 --> 05:01.533
I mean, I used to be
just in my office,

05:01.534 --> 05:04.706
coming up with, you know,
crazy ideas.

05:10.699 --> 05:12.499
It's a big thing.

05:12.500 --> 05:15.499
There is a general sense waiting
for this machine to start,

05:15.500 --> 05:19.833
this massive machine that has
taken so many years to build.

05:19.834 --> 05:23.533
We are all in great anticipation
of what it might find.

05:23.534 --> 05:25.899
And every time
there's even a rumor

05:25.900 --> 05:28.166
that a new particle
is discovered...

05:28.167 --> 05:30.365
even before it turns on...

05:30.366 --> 05:34.932
the entire field
goes into a fever pitch.

05:34.933 --> 05:39.934
The experiment was designed
initially in the mid '80s

05:39.935 --> 05:43.100
and has taken
this long to construct.

05:43.101 --> 05:47.900
There are 10,000 people
of over 100 nationalities.

05:47.901 --> 05:49.666
That includes countries

05:49.667 --> 05:51.767
which are mortal enemies
of each other,

05:51.768 --> 05:55.533
like India and Pakistan,
and Georgia and Russia,

05:55.534 --> 05:57.234
and Iran and Israel.

05:57.235 --> 06:00.167
All have physicists
working on this machine.

06:00.168 --> 06:03.003
These big blue things
are 7-ton

06:04.002 --> 06:05.768
superconducting magnets,

06:05.769 --> 06:08.435
which have to be cooled
with liquid helium

06:08.436 --> 06:10.601
to the coldest temperatures
on Earth,

06:10.602 --> 06:12.001
colder than empty space.

06:13.001 --> 06:16.402
There are 100,000 computers

06:16.403 --> 06:20.101
connected all over the world
to deal with the data.

06:20.103 --> 06:22.868
In fact, the worldwide web
was invented at CERN

06:22.869 --> 06:24.402
so that physicists
all over the planet

06:24.403 --> 06:26.234
could share the data.

06:26.235 --> 06:29.902
The United States was building
a machine just like this,

06:29.903 --> 06:33.069
in fact, a bigger machine,
in Texas,

06:33.070 --> 06:37.535
but they ran into
a small technical difficulty.

06:37.536 --> 06:42.269
- I doubt anyone believes
that the most pressing issues

06:42.270 --> 06:48.035
facing the nation include
an insufficient understanding

06:48.035 --> 06:50.935
of the origins of the universe.

06:50.935 --> 06:54.270
- Unfortunately, the
Superconducting Super Collider

06:54.271 --> 06:57.769
was canceled by Congress
in 1993.

06:57.770 --> 06:59.834
- And finally, he's saying,
"Well, if we don't do it,

06:59.836 --> 07:01.535
the Europeans will do it."

07:01.536 --> 07:03.403
Let them do it!

07:03.404 --> 07:05.569
We'll steal their technology
like they steal our technology.

07:05.570 --> 07:08.335
It got very political.

07:08.336 --> 07:13.003
It was very expensive,
very complicated.

07:13.004 --> 07:15.337
It's hard for physicists
to explain

07:15.338 --> 07:18.069
why we do
these kinds of experiments.

07:18.070 --> 07:22.268
The purpose of the machine
is not military application.

07:22.270 --> 07:24.436
It's not commercial application.

07:24.437 --> 07:28.270
It's to understand something
about the basic laws of physics.

07:28.271 --> 07:31.371
There are two kinds
of particle physicists:

07:31.372 --> 07:33.271
there are the experimentalists.

07:33.272 --> 07:37.070
They built the big machines,
run the experiments,

07:37.071 --> 07:39.905
analyze the data,
and try to discover things,

07:40.905 --> 07:43.405
like new particles;

07:43.406 --> 07:46.905
And then there are
the theorists, like me.

07:47.903 --> 07:50.037
We construct the theories

07:50.038 --> 07:53.537
that try to explain everything
we see in nature.

07:53.538 --> 07:58.037
Without us, the experimentalists
are in the dark,

07:58.038 --> 08:00.105
but without them,

08:00.106 --> 08:02.541
we'll never know the truth.

08:05.672 --> 08:07.737
- I mean, if you go,
it won't be so terrible.

08:07.738 --> 08:10.005
When I was at Stanford,
I had a mentor:

08:10.006 --> 08:12.437
Savas Dimopoulos.

08:12.438 --> 08:16.672
Savas only likes to work
on the biggest puzzles.

08:16.673 --> 08:18.539
Now, just for fun,

08:18.540 --> 08:21.671
I wanted to tell you that the
enabling technologies that...

08:21.671 --> 08:24.272
- He has
some of the most famous theories

08:24.273 --> 08:26.405
that will be tested at the LHC,

08:26.406 --> 08:30.240
but he doesn't know
if any of them are true,

08:30.241 --> 08:33.773
so there's an intensity with
which he approaches physics.

08:33.774 --> 08:37.405
If he works on a paper that
could result in a Nobel Prize,

08:37.407 --> 08:40.272
he doesn't allow more
than three people on the paper,

08:40.273 --> 08:42.337
because you can only share
the Nobel Prize

08:42.339 --> 08:44.005
with three people.

08:44.006 --> 08:47.506
That's the level
at which he's operating

08:47.507 --> 08:49.541
and the impact
he's trying to have.

08:49.542 --> 08:52.066
- Takes us beyond the
confines of atomic physics.

08:52.840 --> 08:54.507
In particle physics,

08:54.508 --> 08:58.072
you have to have a threshold
amount of intelligence,

08:58.073 --> 09:00.739
whatever that means.

09:00.741 --> 09:03.272
But the thing
that differentiates scientists

09:03.273 --> 09:06.874
is purely an artistic ability

09:06.875 --> 09:11.507
to discern what is a good idea,

09:11.508 --> 09:13.173
what is a beautiful idea,

09:13.174 --> 09:15.607
what is worth spending time on,

09:15.608 --> 09:18.739
and, most importantly,

09:18.740 --> 09:23.840
what is a problem that
is sufficiently interesting,

09:23.842 --> 09:26.174
yet sufficiently difficult

09:26.175 --> 09:28.873
that it hasn't yet been solved,

09:28.874 --> 09:34.574
but the time
for solving it has come now?

09:58.177 --> 10:00.741
- So people have been waiting
for this experiment,

10:00.742 --> 10:02.778
the LHC, for a very long time.

10:03.440 --> 10:05.174
Nothing like it
has ever happened.

10:05.175 --> 10:06.674
All the superlatives
are justified.

10:06.675 --> 10:09.842
This is the case
where the hype is...

10:09.844 --> 10:11.741
the hype
is approximately accurate.

10:11.742 --> 10:14.276
To get, you know, 3,000 people

10:14.277 --> 10:15.708
to work
on an experiment together,

10:15.709 --> 10:17.408
whose goal is to understand

10:17.409 --> 10:19.575
what's going on at distances
a thousand times smaller

10:19.576 --> 10:21.242
than the proton...

10:21.243 --> 10:24.210
this is... this is a really
extraordinary testament

10:24.211 --> 10:28.842
to what...
to some of the highest ideals

10:28.843 --> 10:31.109
we can have as human beings.

10:31.110 --> 10:32.777
It's...

10:32.778 --> 10:35.776
- Nima and I got our PhDs
around the same time.

10:35.776 --> 10:37.575
He's a couple years ahead of me.

10:37.576 --> 10:41.711
And Nima
is the star of our generation,

10:41.712 --> 10:45.611
and he's the guy we all followed
and looked up to

10:45.612 --> 10:47.008
and tried to keep up with

10:47.009 --> 10:50.082
and tried to outpace
if we could.

10:54.078 --> 10:55.842
Since the mid '70s,

10:55.843 --> 10:58.577
we've had an amazingly
successful theory of nature

10:58.578 --> 11:01.211
that we call the Standard Model
of particle physics.

11:01.212 --> 11:03.877
But sitting in the heart
of the theory is a sickness,

11:03.878 --> 11:07.444
very, very glaring
conceptual problems

11:07.446 --> 11:09.654
that infected
this fantastic understanding.

11:11.544 --> 11:13.877
Why is the universe big?

11:13.878 --> 11:16.544
Why is gravity so much weaker
than all the other forces?

11:16.545 --> 11:19.277
The kinds of answers that this
theory gives to these questions

11:19.278 --> 11:21.878
seems so patently absurd

11:21.879 --> 11:26.111
that we think that we're missing
something very, very big.

11:26.112 --> 11:28.244
And on top of all of that,

11:28.245 --> 11:30.412
there is one prediction
of this theory...

11:30.413 --> 11:32.011
absolutely crucial
for it to even make

11:32.012 --> 11:34.111
internal theoretical sense...

11:34.112 --> 11:36.578
and this is
the famous Higgs particle.

11:36.579 --> 11:38.378
The Higgs, or something like it,
must show up.

11:38.379 --> 11:39.880
If it doesn't show up,

11:39.881 --> 11:42.211
there's something
truly, deeply wrong,

11:42.212 --> 11:43.545
very, very, deeply wrong

11:43.546 --> 11:45.412
with the way
we think about physics.

11:45.413 --> 11:46.846
There are strong reasons

11:46.847 --> 11:48.211
to think that some
of these questions

11:48.212 --> 11:50.279
will find answers at the LHC.

11:50.280 --> 11:51.711
There's been no shortage
of ideas

11:51.712 --> 11:54.079
for what they might be,

11:54.080 --> 11:57.546
but this is really
this generation of people's...

11:57.547 --> 11:59.545
my generation of people's...
only shot.

12:12.414 --> 12:14.580
Ah, so the boss comes.

12:23.249 --> 12:26.613
I first came to CERN in 1987.

12:26.614 --> 12:29.745
I was a very young
undergraduate student,

12:29.746 --> 12:32.748
and I remember the first time
I entered the site.

12:32.749 --> 12:35.281
I was a bit scared
by the corridors

12:35.282 --> 12:37.781
in the CERN main site,

12:37.782 --> 12:40.548
so I was almost lost
in those corridors.

12:40.549 --> 12:42.280
For me, it has been
a wonderful experience,

12:42.281 --> 12:44.013
because I had the chance
of being involved

12:44.014 --> 12:45.780
right from the beginning

12:45.781 --> 12:49.781
and to see, really, an
experiment from starting and...

12:49.782 --> 12:51.448
from zero, essentially.

12:51.449 --> 12:53.248
- I've seen two inventors
place out of the ten,

12:53.249 --> 12:54.681
and we probably have seen...

12:54.682 --> 12:56.215
- I don't think
I can describe right now

12:56.216 --> 12:58.080
the excitement about first beam.

12:58.081 --> 13:00.514
I mean, the entire control room

13:00.515 --> 13:04.948
is like a group
of six-year-olds

13:04.949 --> 13:07.416
whose birthday is next week,
you know,

13:07.417 --> 13:08.782
and there's going to be cake,

13:08.783 --> 13:10.381
and there's going to be
presents,

13:10.382 --> 13:12.047
and all their friends
are going to be there,

13:12.048 --> 13:13.517
and they just, you know...

13:13.517 --> 13:16.115
they just know
it's going to be great.

13:16.116 --> 13:18.181
You know,
they're kind of scattered,

13:18.182 --> 13:20.414
and I can't imagine, 'cause
they're not that big, right?

13:20.415 --> 13:21.849
I've been a postdoc here
for a year,

13:21.849 --> 13:23.214
so I'm a relative newcomer.

13:23.215 --> 13:24.898
But my timing
is sort of perfect.

13:25.583 --> 13:27.283
I mean,
to be on the ground floor

13:27.284 --> 13:28.882
when the data first comes...

13:28.883 --> 13:30.115
it's awesome.

13:30.116 --> 13:32.549
That means I have 5,000 emails.

13:32.550 --> 13:34.915
There's a huge difference

13:34.916 --> 13:37.783
between theorists
and experimentalists.

13:37.784 --> 13:39.849
I mean, when I started college,

13:39.850 --> 13:43.382
I absolutely did not
want to do physics.

13:43.383 --> 13:45.803
Physics meant to me
everything that was boring:

13:46.550 --> 13:50.516
textbooks, theories, proofs.

13:50.517 --> 13:52.779
But then I discovered
the experimental side,

13:53.551 --> 13:57.518
and the experimental side
is the hands-on aspect.

13:57.519 --> 13:59.382
It's about taking a theory,

13:59.383 --> 14:03.250
which is abstract,
and making it real.

14:03.251 --> 14:04.829
How do you build an experiment

14:05.551 --> 14:09.385
to discover something
that the theory predicts?

14:09.386 --> 14:12.552
And that aspect is what I love.

14:27.253 --> 14:29.951
Of course, when constructing
the whole thing,

14:29.952 --> 14:31.884
we several times thought,

14:31.885 --> 14:34.784
"What if the whole thing
just does not work?"

14:34.785 --> 14:36.718
I really believe now
this will work,

14:36.719 --> 14:39.750
but the next thing is,
will we ever find something?

14:39.751 --> 14:42.752
So maybe we will
just find nothing new.

14:42.753 --> 14:45.052
It would be a catastrophe
for physics.

14:45.053 --> 14:46.917
We would, somehow...

14:46.918 --> 14:49.584
none of the open questions
which we have at the moment

14:49.585 --> 14:52.718
would've been answered.

14:52.720 --> 14:58.851
- So the LHC is basically the
most fundamental of experiments.

14:58.852 --> 15:01.620
It's like what any child
would design as an experiment.

15:01.621 --> 15:05.753
You take two things,
and you smash them together.

15:05.754 --> 15:08.684
And you get a lot of stuff that
comes out of that collision,

15:08.685 --> 15:11.919
and you try
to understand that stuff.

15:11.921 --> 15:13.785
Now, in this case,

15:13.786 --> 15:16.851
what we're smashing together
is tiny protons,

15:16.852 --> 15:20.353
which are inside the center
of every atom.

15:20.354 --> 15:23.118
And in order to get them
going as fast as possible,

15:23.119 --> 15:27.185
we have to build
this huge 17-mile ring,

15:27.186 --> 15:30.753
and we run those protons
around the ring multiple times

15:30.754 --> 15:34.420
to build up speed,
almost to the speed of light,

15:34.420 --> 15:37.719
and then we collide two beams
going in opposite directions

15:37.720 --> 15:39.621
at four points,

15:39.622 --> 15:42.953
and at those four points
are four different experiments:

15:42.954 --> 15:47.920
ATLAS, LHCb, CMS, and ALICE.

15:47.921 --> 15:49.888
Now, I work
on the ATLAS experiment.

15:49.889 --> 15:52.423
And ATLAS is like
a huge seven-story camera

15:53.421 --> 15:57.588
that takes a snapshot
of every single collision,

15:57.589 --> 16:00.355
and that's billions
of collisions.

16:00.356 --> 16:04.288
And the hope is that we'll see
the very famous Higgs particle.

16:04.289 --> 16:07.088
But every time we've turned on
the new accelerator

16:07.089 --> 16:08.521
at a higher energy,

16:08.522 --> 16:10.288
we've always been surprised.

16:10.289 --> 16:13.788
So the real hope
is that we'll see the Higgs,

16:13.789 --> 16:16.157
but that there's also something
amazingly new.

16:18.723 --> 16:23.889
- You can liken it to
when we put a man on the moon.

16:23.890 --> 16:25.586
It's that level
of collaborative effort.

16:25.587 --> 16:27.555
I would say,
even bigger than that.

16:27.556 --> 16:29.221
This is closer to something like

16:29.222 --> 16:31.954
human beings
building the Pyramids.

16:31.955 --> 16:33.422
Why did they do it?

16:33.423 --> 16:34.723
Why are we doing it?

16:34.724 --> 16:36.422
We actually have two answers.

16:36.423 --> 16:38.689
One answer
is what we tell people,

16:38.690 --> 16:41.523
and the other answer
is the truth.

16:42.757 --> 16:44.622
I'll tell you both.

16:44.623 --> 16:47.421
And there's nothing incorrect
about the first answer.

16:47.422 --> 16:50.355
It's just... it doesn't... it's
not the thing that drives us.

16:50.356 --> 16:52.122
It's not how we think about it,

16:52.123 --> 16:54.122
but it's something
you can say quickly,

16:54.358 --> 16:57.756
and the person you're talking to
won't, you know,

16:57.757 --> 17:01.123
<i>get diverted or pass out
or pick up the SkyMall catalog</i>

17:01.124 --> 17:03.555
if you happen to be next to them
on an airplane.

17:03.556 --> 17:05.089
Answer number one:

17:05.090 --> 17:09.189
we are reproducing the physics,

17:09.190 --> 17:12.191
the conditions,
just after the big bang.

17:12.192 --> 17:14.056
We're doing it in this collider,

17:14.057 --> 17:16.856
and we're reproducing that
so we can see what it was like

17:16.857 --> 17:18.623
when the universe just started.

17:18.624 --> 17:20.055
This is what we tell people.

17:20.057 --> 17:22.723
Okay, answer two:

17:22.723 --> 17:25.391
we are trying to understand
the basic laws of nature.

17:25.392 --> 17:27.957
It sounds slightly more mild,

17:27.958 --> 17:31.791
but this is really where we are
and what we're trying to do.

17:31.792 --> 17:35.223
We study particles,
because just after the big bang,

17:35.224 --> 17:37.424
all there was was particles,

17:37.425 --> 17:42.524
and they carried the information
about how our universe started

17:42.525 --> 17:45.391
and how it got to be
the way it is

17:45.392 --> 17:48.756
and its future.

17:48.757 --> 17:51.225
At the beginning of the 1900s,

17:51.226 --> 17:54.791
it became clear
that all known matter,

17:54.792 --> 17:56.591
everything that we know about,

17:56.592 --> 17:58.092
is made of atoms,

17:58.093 --> 18:01.626
and that atoms are made
of just three particles:

18:01.627 --> 18:05.628
the electron, the proton,
and the neutron.

18:07.626 --> 18:11.358
In the '30s,
other particles were discovered,

18:11.359 --> 18:13.426
and by the 1960s,

18:13.427 --> 18:15.459
there were hundreds
of new particles,

18:15.460 --> 18:18.426
with a new particle discovered
every week.

18:18.427 --> 18:21.058
And there was mass confusion,

18:21.059 --> 18:25.192
until a number
of theorists realized

18:25.193 --> 18:27.427
that there was a simple
mathematical structure

18:27.428 --> 18:30.225
that explained all of this,

18:30.226 --> 18:32.025
that most of these particles

18:32.026 --> 18:33.793
were made of the same
three little bits

18:33.794 --> 18:35.794
we call quarks,

18:35.794 --> 18:37.073
and that there are only
a handful

18:37.260 --> 18:39.126
of truly fundamental particles,

18:39.127 --> 18:42.058
which all fit together
in a nice, neat pattern.

18:42.059 --> 18:45.029
And there was born
the Standard Model.

18:48.026 --> 18:50.925
Eventually, all the particles
in the theory

18:50.926 --> 18:55.062
were discovered,
except one: the Higgs.

18:57.060 --> 19:01.226
And the Higgs
is unlike any other particle.

19:01.227 --> 19:04.559
It's the linchpin
of the Standard Model.

19:04.560 --> 19:08.294
Its theory was written down
in the 1960s by Peter Higgs

19:08.295 --> 19:10.760
and a number of other theorists.

19:10.761 --> 19:13.528
We believe
it is the crucial piece

19:13.529 --> 19:16.459
responsible
for holding matter together.

19:16.460 --> 19:20.760
It is connected to a field
which fills all of space

19:20.761 --> 19:24.261
and which gives particles,
like the electron, mass

19:24.262 --> 19:27.295
and allowed them
to get caught in atoms

19:27.296 --> 19:30.196
and thus is responsible
for the creation of atoms,

19:30.197 --> 19:32.795
molecules, planets, and people.

19:32.796 --> 19:36.230
Without the Higgs, life
as we know it wouldn't exist.

19:38.228 --> 19:40.061
But to prove that it's true,

19:40.062 --> 19:43.395
we have to smash particles
together at high enough energy

19:43.397 --> 19:48.062
to disturb the field
and create a Higgs particle.

19:48.063 --> 19:49.928
If the Higgs exists,

19:49.929 --> 19:53.128
the LHC is the machine
that will discover it.

19:53.128 --> 19:55.761
- Let's assume you're successful
and everything comes out okay.

19:55.762 --> 19:57.861
- Sure.
- What do we gain from it?

19:57.862 --> 19:59.463
What's the economic return?

19:59.463 --> 20:01.060
How do you justify all this?

20:01.061 --> 20:02.962
By the way, I am an economist.

20:02.963 --> 20:06.029
I don't hold it against you.

20:06.030 --> 20:10.030
The question
by an economist was,

20:10.031 --> 20:13.930
"What is the financial gain of
running an experiment like this

20:13.931 --> 20:17.529
and the discoveries that we
will make in this experiment?"

20:17.530 --> 20:19.963
And it's a very,
very simple answer.

20:19.964 --> 20:23.230
I have no idea.

20:23.231 --> 20:24.762
We have no idea.

20:24.763 --> 20:26.796
When radio waves
were discovered,

20:26.797 --> 20:28.728
they weren't called radio waves,

20:28.729 --> 20:30.629
because there were no radios.

20:30.630 --> 20:33.563
They were discovered
as some sort of radiation.

20:33.564 --> 20:37.362
Basic science
for big breakthroughs

20:37.363 --> 20:39.062
needs to occur at a level

20:39.063 --> 20:41.798
where you're not asking,
"What is the economic gain?"

20:41.799 --> 20:44.097
You're asking,
"What do we not know,

20:44.098 --> 20:45.898
and where
can we make progress?"

20:45.899 --> 20:49.062
So what is the LHC good for?

20:49.063 --> 20:52.963
Could be nothing other than
just understanding everything.

21:03.299 --> 21:06.364
- The first time
I ever saw ATLAS was in 2005.

21:06.365 --> 21:08.697
I had come out just to see
what ATLAS would look like

21:08.698 --> 21:11.231
because there was a possibility
that I could be working on it

21:11.232 --> 21:14.264
as a postdoc.

21:14.266 --> 21:17.931
I can remember walking in
and just being like...

21:17.932 --> 21:19.564
You know, just stunned.

21:19.565 --> 21:21.398
I mean, me, stunned,
you know, just, you know,

21:21.399 --> 21:23.464
already kind of having an idea
of the magnitude.

21:23.465 --> 21:25.764
People tell you,
"Oh, it's five stories tall."

21:25.765 --> 21:27.431
And you go, "Oh, okay,
five stories tall."

21:27.432 --> 21:29.298
And then you see.

21:29.299 --> 21:34.969
Five stories completely filled
with microelectronics...

21:37.967 --> 21:41.632
All custom designed,
all hand-soldered.

21:41.633 --> 21:46.267
You know, it's like as if
it's a five-story Swiss watch.

