38:19.099 --> 38:21.667
and warming up the magnets
needs to be done

38:21.668 --> 38:26.165
on a very slow pace and...
in order not to break them...

38:26.166 --> 38:28.743
then you can investigate
and cool them down again.

38:50.267 --> 38:52.401
- The world's largest
atom smasher,

38:52.402 --> 38:55.267
the Large Hadron Collider,

38:55.268 --> 38:57.400
is to be shut down
for at least two months.

38:57.401 --> 38:59.668
CERN, the European Organization
for Nuclear Research...

38:59.669 --> 39:02.333
- Scientists at CERN are trying
to put on a brave face.

39:02.333 --> 39:05.334
A faulty electrical connection
between two magnets

39:05.335 --> 39:06.900
led to a ton of liquid helium

39:06.901 --> 39:09.668
being leaked into
the 27-kilometer tunnel.

39:09.668 --> 39:11.768
The first high-speed
particle collisions

39:11.769 --> 39:13.802
were due to take place
later this month.

39:13.803 --> 39:15.501
The goal now

39:15.502 --> 39:20.786
is simply to get this
vastly complex machine working.

40:08.137 --> 40:09.736
Fucking hell, look at that.

40:09.737 --> 40:11.771
This is just unbelievable.

40:11.772 --> 40:14.937
You've got magnets
just sheared off their jacks.

40:14.938 --> 40:16.725
We've actually
put in enough energy

40:17.003 --> 40:21.135
to melt it and to vaporize
a whole tube of...

40:21.136 --> 40:24.505
- And the stuff's all covered in
a sort of black, metallic dust.

40:24.506 --> 40:25.770
Completely catastrophic, eh?

40:25.771 --> 40:27.436
Completely catastrophic.

40:27.437 --> 40:29.403
- There's no more vacuum
in the beam vacuum,

40:29.404 --> 40:32.270
so can as well open it up and
see whether there's any dust,

40:32.271 --> 40:33.604
because if there's dust,

40:33.605 --> 40:35.736
it means
we have to clean all the way

40:35.737 --> 40:37.169
until it's...

40:37.170 --> 40:38.837
I hope, in the worst case,

40:38.838 --> 40:44.947
we have not to take out
more than 20 or so magnets.

40:53.938 --> 40:58.138
Both my family and my students

40:58.139 --> 41:02.171
detect a definite level of...

41:02.172 --> 41:05.509
let's say pessimism
and disappointment.

41:08.506 --> 41:10.671
The built expectation

41:10.672 --> 41:14.271
that now we were going to know
the truth,

41:14.272 --> 41:16.605
it fizzled and delayed,

41:16.606 --> 41:19.010
and it's just, uh...

41:24.005 --> 41:26.909
I thought
I was stronger than this.

41:28.907 --> 41:31.971
It surprised me.

41:31.972 --> 41:34.172
- I did say that I thought
it was a mistake

41:34.174 --> 41:35.906
for CERN to have
this gigantic celebration

41:35.906 --> 41:38.573
for things just when
it just had a few protons

41:38.574 --> 41:40.973
wandering around in one
direction around the ring,

41:40.974 --> 41:43.407
that it was just a bad idea
to have so much hoopla

41:43.408 --> 41:45.106
before anything
was actually happening.

41:45.108 --> 41:46.606
At the time
when people were asking me

41:46.607 --> 41:48.005
if I was going to CERN
to celebrate,

41:48.006 --> 41:49.572
I said, "I'm going to go to CERN

41:49.574 --> 41:51.439
"when there's a reason
to celebrate, you know,

41:51.440 --> 41:53.238
"when things are colliding
into each other,

41:53.239 --> 41:54.840
"when something
is starting to happen,

41:54.841 --> 41:57.773
not for some crappy PR reason."

41:57.774 --> 41:59.340
And that backfired.

41:59.341 --> 42:01.140
That, I think... really,
that really backfired,

42:01.141 --> 42:03.075
and I think
that was a PR disaster.

42:03.075 --> 42:05.273
It was a PR disaster
largely of CERN's own making.

42:05.274 --> 42:06.974
You don't go around, you know,

42:06.975 --> 42:09.708
having gigantic parties
before anything has happened.

42:36.242 --> 42:39.941
- So the magnets that have
come out are being refurbished,

42:39.942 --> 42:41.808
and so they're sort of
trundling through

42:41.809 --> 42:43.508
about six magnets a week now.

42:43.509 --> 42:46.242
So that's no longer
the bottleneck.

42:46.243 --> 42:48.274
Now they're kind of
getting to the state

42:48.275 --> 42:50.808
where they're ready to start
redoing the interconnects

42:50.809 --> 42:52.642
in the tunnel,

42:52.643 --> 42:56.107
and they're already about a week
or two behind on that.

42:56.108 --> 42:57.608
Given the complexity...

42:57.609 --> 42:59.276
- The other thing
is that they're drilling

42:59.277 --> 43:00.975
these bloody holes
in the magnets.

43:00.976 --> 43:03.508
- Because they, like...
- what I heard this last time,

43:03.509 --> 43:05.741
they were saying that
all their tools are breaking

43:05.742 --> 43:07.175
and that sort of business.

43:07.176 --> 43:08.342
- But it begs the question,
of course,

43:08.343 --> 43:09.941
you know, what are the risks?

43:09.942 --> 43:11.741
I mean, you kind of basically,
you're going...

43:11.742 --> 43:12.976
I don't know.

43:12.977 --> 43:14.509
We didn't actually think so much

43:14.510 --> 43:16.275
about the collateral effects
of the helium.

43:16.276 --> 43:17.510
- Nobody has.
- Yeah, nobody.

43:17.510 --> 43:19.009
- Yeah.
- Nobody.

43:19.010 --> 43:20.742
Well, there's been
a lot of investigations

43:20.743 --> 43:22.342
into the cause
of the original problem,

43:22.344 --> 43:24.308
and the general agreement
is that we run

43:24.309 --> 43:26.642
at half design energy.

43:26.643 --> 43:29.909
- Experimentalists
aren't going to be happy.

43:29.910 --> 43:31.411
Well...

43:31.412 --> 43:34.576
- So, yeah...
so the latest schedule is this:

43:34.577 --> 43:36.611
we just put out is D-Day,

43:36.612 --> 43:38.742
beams back on
the 21st of September.

43:38.743 --> 43:40.975
Isn't that a bit optimistic?

43:40.976 --> 43:43.610
Isn't that a bit
optimistic for, uh, this year?

43:43.611 --> 43:45.610
- When you're dealing
with something

43:45.611 --> 43:47.276
that is a long-term project...

43:47.277 --> 43:49.578
and the LHC
is a long-term project.

43:49.579 --> 43:52.177
It's a 20-year project.

43:52.178 --> 43:54.077
You can't think about the end.

43:54.078 --> 43:55.516
Ever.

43:58.512 --> 44:01.177
If you start out
a marathon thinking,

44:01.178 --> 44:03.077
"I can't wait
to get to the finish line;

44:03.078 --> 44:05.910
"I'm gonna have my Gatorade
at the finish line;

44:05.911 --> 44:09.077
I'm gonna have my greasy french
fries at the finish line,"

44:09.078 --> 44:11.311
or whatever motivates you...

44:11.312 --> 44:13.245
if you start thinking that
at mile one

44:13.246 --> 44:16.078
and it's, like,
ten minutes into the race,

44:16.079 --> 44:17.744
and you're thinking to yourself,

44:17.745 --> 44:20.345
"Wow, I'm only at mile one.

44:20.346 --> 44:26.079
I've got 25.2 miles to go."

44:26.080 --> 44:28.344
And if you're thinking that
at the start,

44:28.345 --> 44:29.612
then you're done.

44:29.613 --> 44:30.946
Mentally, you are done.

44:32.479 --> 44:34.793
- This is what doing
discovery physics means.

44:35.779 --> 44:37.746
This is what doing
discovery means.

44:59.314 --> 45:01.979
Why do people have curiosity?

45:01.980 --> 45:06.414
Why do we care about how
distant parts of the universe,

45:06.415 --> 45:08.512
things that happened
billion years ago,

45:08.513 --> 45:09.980
like the big bang,

45:09.981 --> 45:11.581
why do we find them
that interesting?

45:11.582 --> 45:14.279
It doesn't affect
what we do day-to-day.

45:14.280 --> 45:17.947
But nevertheless,
once you have curiosity,

45:17.948 --> 45:19.913
you can't control it.

45:23.814 --> 45:26.014
- It'll ask questions
about the universe.

45:26.015 --> 45:29.746
It will ask questions
about harmonic patterns

45:29.747 --> 45:34.447
that create art, music.

45:34.448 --> 45:36.415
- That's a sculpture?
- That's a sculpture.

45:36.415 --> 45:38.482
- Yeah, doesn't it look like
a bunch of broken tiles?

45:38.483 --> 45:40.146
- That's what it's supposed
to look like.

45:40.147 --> 45:41.980
And it's, uh...
and when I saw it,

45:41.982 --> 45:44.282
I thought it was just rubble
left over from the construction.

45:44.283 --> 45:45.515
Right, yeah.

45:45.516 --> 45:46.848
- You can, in principle,
move it.

45:46.849 --> 45:48.448
- So people go up
and move pieces?

45:48.449 --> 45:51.447
- No, people don't.
- But people could.

45:51.448 --> 45:53.248
Why would they have it
so you can move it around

45:53.249 --> 45:54.781
if you weren't going
to move it around?

45:54.782 --> 45:56.248
No, I think you're right.

45:56.248 --> 45:57.913
- I think you're allowed
to move it around.

45:57.914 --> 45:59.814
- It's certainly
a different experience of it.

45:59.815 --> 46:01.180
I agree.

46:01.182 --> 46:03.114
See, I thought
that that belonged here.

46:03.115 --> 46:04.483
It's just...
it's the perfect spot.

46:04.484 --> 46:05.915
- It certainly
changes everything.

46:05.916 --> 46:08.515
- It does.
- Slate and granite.

46:08.516 --> 46:11.647
I guess that's the granite,
and that's the slate.

46:11.648 --> 46:13.419
Hmm.

46:16.417 --> 46:19.015
It's interesting.

46:19.016 --> 46:20.683
- There's something
philosophically

46:20.684 --> 46:23.349
about this piece of art
that bothers me.

46:23.350 --> 46:25.682
It's taking a lot of
sort of random things

46:25.683 --> 46:26.982
and making some order out of it.

46:26.983 --> 46:28.515
Yes.

46:28.516 --> 46:30.282
- It's trying to make order
out of something

46:30.283 --> 46:31.816
where there isn't any,

46:31.817 --> 46:33.849
instead of taking things
that don't seem ordered

46:33.850 --> 46:36.615
and figuring out
that there is order.

46:36.616 --> 46:40.251
- The way we try to reduce
the complexity of the world

46:40.252 --> 46:43.748
is by looking for patterns,

46:43.749 --> 46:46.016
what we call symmetries.

46:46.017 --> 46:49.316
We take all the particles
we know today,

46:49.317 --> 46:50.749
and we attempt to fit them

46:50.750 --> 46:52.748
into some kind
of underlying structure.

46:53.651 --> 46:57.085
Are they the remnants
of some more beautiful

46:57.086 --> 47:01.286
and complete picture
of the laws of nature?

47:03.284 --> 47:07.951
It's like, you go to Egypt,
and you see ruins.

47:07.952 --> 47:10.484
If you look at it the right way,

47:10.485 --> 47:11.641
I could draw a pyramid

47:12.618 --> 47:14.650
and see that
these chunks of stone

47:14.651 --> 47:17.983
are actually the remains
of something very clean

47:17.985 --> 47:19.483
and very symmetric,

47:19.484 --> 47:22.417
very beautiful.

47:22.418 --> 47:25.753
We know that the Standard Model
is incomplete.

47:27.751 --> 47:29.984
We know that there's
other stuff out there,

47:29.985 --> 47:33.185
that there are other particles
that we haven't seen yet.

47:33.186 --> 47:36.285
Dark matter
is a speculated particle

47:36.286 --> 47:39.917
which we think
actually dominates the universe,

47:39.918 --> 47:42.418
and yet we've never seen it
directly,

47:42.419 --> 47:45.118
and it's not part
of the Standard Model.

47:45.119 --> 47:47.851
That's one of those rocks.

47:47.852 --> 47:50.519
We think, possibly,

47:50.520 --> 47:54.185
that that and many other
particles are still out there

47:54.186 --> 47:56.588
and are all part
of a much bigger symmetry,

47:57.587 --> 47:59.252
a much bigger theory

47:59.253 --> 48:02.124
that includes the Standard
Model, but much more.

48:08.118 --> 48:11.953
The most popular theory
is called supersymmetry,

48:11.954 --> 48:14.119
or SUSY for short.

48:14.120 --> 48:18.320
Supersymmetry was a theory
that sort of started to develop

48:18.321 --> 48:19.785
in the late '70s.

48:19.786 --> 48:22.352
Savas was one
of the first authors

48:22.353 --> 48:26.620
of the first theories
of supersymmetry.

48:26.621 --> 48:29.821
- It is the unfathomable
depths of...

48:29.822 --> 48:35.688
- Supersymmetry is our best
guess of what else is out there,

48:35.689 --> 48:37.787
the bigger theory
that incorporates

48:37.788 --> 48:39.354
our current theories,

48:39.355 --> 48:41.653
the Standard Model.

48:41.654 --> 48:43.786
But for it to be true,

48:43.787 --> 48:47.364
we have to discover
those other particles.

48:57.351 --> 48:59.454
- If I could choose a dream
of any theory

48:59.455 --> 49:01.187
that the LHC could find,

49:01.188 --> 49:03.821
actually, I would love
for them to see supersymmetry.

49:03.822 --> 49:09.755
Supersymmetry says,
for every type of particle,

49:09.756 --> 49:11.287
say the electron,

49:11.289 --> 49:13.955
there's a heavy superpartner.

49:13.956 --> 49:15.653
So you have the...

49:15.654 --> 49:17.622
and they have really stupid
names, unfortunately,

49:17.623 --> 49:19.154
called the selectron.

49:19.155 --> 49:21.354
You just add an S to the name.
The squark.

49:21.355 --> 49:25.422
Uh, the sup, the sdown.

49:25.422 --> 49:27.255
Supersymmetry, or SUSY,

49:27.257 --> 49:30.522
is extremely important
for the theoretical community

49:30.523 --> 49:33.156
because it solves
many mathematical problems

49:33.157 --> 49:35.088
with the Standard model.

49:35.089 --> 49:38.822
Now, experimentally, it would be
the experimentalists' dream.

49:38.823 --> 49:42.022
You know, tons of particles
that are just coming out,

49:42.023 --> 49:43.855
and you just don't even know
what to do with...

49:43.856 --> 49:45.689
you know, can't even
write the data fast enough

49:45.690 --> 49:47.022
in order to discover them.

49:47.023 --> 49:50.293
So that'd be my dream.

49:53.095 --> 49:55.356
It used to be
that in the control room life,

49:55.357 --> 49:56.656
it was kind of a luxury.

49:56.657 --> 49:58.488
You know, you could kind of...

49:58.489 --> 50:00.521
you could, you know, kind
of style your hair for the day

50:00.523 --> 50:02.655
because you didn't have to wear
a hard helmet all day.

50:02.656 --> 50:04.357
You could wear nice shoes,
you know,

50:04.358 --> 50:06.425
because you were in
the control room environment.

50:06.426 --> 50:09.090
Now, it's all back to, you know,

50:09.091 --> 50:11.257
bring the dirtiest clothes
that you own to work

50:11.458 --> 50:13.756
because you're gonna be crawling
around in, like,

50:13.757 --> 50:15.457
you know, hard helmets,
steel-toed boots.

50:15.458 --> 50:16.823
Not the most attractive shoes,

50:16.824 --> 50:18.611
but, you know,
I kind of like them.

50:21.258 --> 50:23.091
We're pulling out
the electronics.

50:23.092 --> 50:25.190
We're fixing things that
we didn't actually have time

50:25.191 --> 50:28.358
to get to
during the last shutdown.

50:28.358 --> 50:30.456
The goal of this is
that it would be

50:30.457 --> 50:33.828
in even better shape
for next beam.

50:36.824 --> 50:43.325
Okay, so that is, I think,
all that I have to say.

50:43.326 --> 50:47.091
Hope the theorists
aren't driving you crazy.

50:47.092 --> 50:49.424
Don't listen to them,
by the way,

50:49.425 --> 50:51.357
because theorists,

50:51.358 --> 50:55.259
they can sometimes...

50:56.259 --> 50:57.858
Just telling you.

50:57.859 --> 50:59.624
You got to come back
to the experimental world

50:59.625 --> 51:03.759
so that you can touch bases
with reality.

51:03.760 --> 51:06.793
All right,
I'll talk to you soon.

51:11.020 --> 51:13.492
- One of the most basic facts
about the universe

51:13.493 --> 51:14.693
is that it's big.

51:14.694 --> 51:17.191
So you might wonder,

51:17.192 --> 51:21.025
"Why is the universe big?"

51:21.026 --> 51:23.092
There's actually
a single number,

51:23.093 --> 51:24.692
called
the cosmological constant,

51:24.693 --> 51:26.760
that plays a crucial role

51:26.761 --> 51:29.325
in determining
what the universe looks like.

51:29.326 --> 51:32.093
In fact, around ten years ago,

51:32.094 --> 51:34.925
astronomers discovered
a really remarkable fact:

51:34.926 --> 51:37.826
the universe is getting bigger
and bigger

51:37.827 --> 51:40.262
at a faster and faster rate.

51:42.260 --> 51:45.660
But this rate
is a million, billion,

51:45.661 --> 51:50.292
billion, billion, billion,
billion, billion times slower

51:50.293 --> 51:52.529
than what we'd actually predict.

51:54.127 --> 51:56.695
When you're off by
a factor of a million, billion,

51:56.696 --> 51:58.861
billion, billion, billion,
billion, billion,

51:58.863 --> 52:00.528
there's something very wrong

52:00.529 --> 52:04.794
with your understanding
of basic physics.

52:04.795 --> 52:06.260
Even worse,

52:06.261 --> 52:08.294
this one number,
the cosmological constant,

52:08.295 --> 52:10.626
needs to have
this extremely precise value.

52:10.627 --> 52:13.760
And if the value
is different even by a tiny bit,

52:13.760 --> 52:17.197
we would radically change what
the world looks like around us.

52:20.194 --> 52:22.428
If you saw a situation where,

52:22.429 --> 52:24.794
if the parameter
has a very dangerous value

52:24.795 --> 52:26.828
and you change it a little bit,

52:26.829 --> 52:28.194
the world
would change radically,

52:28.195 --> 52:29.460
and we'd be dead.

52:29.461 --> 52:31.328
We couldn't possibly live.

52:31.328 --> 52:33.160
You would wonder
where that came from.

52:33.161 --> 52:35.661
You know, how is that possible?

52:35.662 --> 52:37.262
So just on the face of it,

52:37.264 --> 52:39.096
you would look at the situation
and say,

52:39.097 --> 52:42.328
"Wow, someone really cared
to put this parameter

52:42.329 --> 52:44.828
"at just the right value
so that we get to be here

52:44.829 --> 52:46.963
"and that
it's a pleasant universe

52:46.964 --> 52:50.197
and really cares a lot."

52:52.195 --> 52:55.366
This is the sort of thing that
really keeps you up at night.

52:56.964 --> 52:59.529
It really makes you wonder,
"Maybe we've got something

52:59.530 --> 53:01.696
"about the whole picture,
the big picture,

53:01.697 --> 53:03.381
totally, totally,
totally wrong."

53:19.264 --> 53:21.963
- Before I went
to elementary school,

53:21.964 --> 53:27.128
my mother started telling me
biblical stories.

53:27.129 --> 53:29.364
She told me that if we are good,

53:29.365 --> 53:31.029
we'll go to paradise,

53:31.030 --> 53:33.534
and we will stay there forever.

53:35.531 --> 53:38.262
And when she said "forever,"

53:38.263 --> 53:41.697
I started panicking.

53:41.698 --> 53:43.196
I kept asking, "Forever?"

53:43.197 --> 53:44.462
"Forever?"

53:44.463 --> 53:46.163
You mean, it never ends?

53:46.164 --> 53:48.798
Like, you wake up,
and you know that then,

53:48.799 --> 53:50.129
you go back to sleep,

53:50.130 --> 53:52.364
and this never ends, never ends,

53:52.365 --> 53:53.836
never ends.

53:57.832 --> 53:59.831
I started crying.

53:59.832 --> 54:01.498
She told me,
"What's wrong with you?

54:01.499 --> 54:02.764
"This is paradise.

54:02.765 --> 54:05.130
"It will be a lot of fun.

54:05.131 --> 54:06.707
You'll be very happy there."

54:15.699 --> 54:18.864
But this idea of eternity,

54:18.865 --> 54:21.699
something infinite,

54:21.700 --> 54:23.998
scared me.

54:47.534 --> 54:49.433
- There is
a scientific alternative

54:49.434 --> 54:51.833
to believing there's
someone out there who loves us,

54:51.834 --> 54:55.499
twiddling the dials very finely
for things to work out.

54:55.500 --> 54:57.932
And this alternative,
said briefly,

54:57.933 --> 55:00.367
is that everything we see
in our observed universe

55:00.368 --> 55:02.532
is actually a very small part

55:02.533 --> 55:06.666
of a much,
much vaster multiverse.

55:06.667 --> 55:08.434
You might
literally imagine that,

55:08.435 --> 55:10.199
from some bird's eye
point of view,

55:10.200 --> 55:13.033
if you went
to enormous distances,

55:13.034 --> 55:15.667
you would see that our universe
is actually a little pocket

55:15.668 --> 55:19.104
inside a vastly bigger space.

55:22.102 --> 55:24.868
In this picture,
these mysterious numbers,

55:24.869 --> 55:26.600
like the cosmological constant,

55:26.601 --> 55:29.837
are actually basically random.

55:31.835 --> 55:35.433
And out there in the multiverse,
next to us somewhere,

55:35.434 --> 55:38.434
is another region
where these numbers take on

55:38.436 --> 55:39.666
some other random value,

55:39.667 --> 55:41.334
and then another region

55:41.335 --> 55:43.535
where they take on
some other random value still.

55:43.536 --> 55:46.268
