saying that new particles

01:12:18.135 --> 01:12:19.400
might be
at even higher energies, so...

01:12:19.401 --> 01:12:21.069
Right.

01:12:21.070 --> 01:12:23.302
- Who knows? I mean,
it always comes differently.

01:12:23.303 --> 01:12:24.968
Who knows if there
are other interesting things.

01:12:24.969 --> 01:12:26.501
You know, somehow
it always comes differently

01:12:26.502 --> 01:12:28.167
than you expect.

01:12:28.168 --> 01:12:30.669
- I know that the theorists
are all up in arms,

01:12:30.670 --> 01:12:32.401
because, you know,
it could be a heavy Higgs,

01:12:32.402 --> 01:12:33.966
but, you know,
I've always said, like,

01:12:33.967 --> 01:12:35.336
the worst-case scenario,

01:12:35.337 --> 01:12:37.502
I think,
would be Higgs and Higgs only.

01:12:37.503 --> 01:12:39.002
- Who knows?
- I know. I know.

01:12:39.003 --> 01:12:40.635
- Come on,
it's just a little excess.

01:12:40.637 --> 01:12:42.502
- If this doesn't show up
by the end of next year,

01:12:42.503 --> 01:12:44.068
then we can change subject,
I think.

01:12:44.069 --> 01:12:46.069
If you don't see
any supersymmetric signal...

01:12:46.070 --> 01:12:48.301
- Well, but if it's 140,
that would be serious.

01:12:48.302 --> 01:12:49.701
Yeah, yeah.

01:12:49.702 --> 01:12:51.980
Yeah.

01:13:02.970 --> 01:13:04.904
Don't tell me.

01:13:04.905 --> 01:13:06.705
This is my nightmare.

01:13:08.703 --> 01:13:11.538
It's only 30 for me.

01:13:15.837 --> 01:13:17.571
At the moment, it's scary.

01:13:17.572 --> 01:13:19.726
- At the moment, it's scary.
- It's scary.

01:13:29.305 --> 01:13:32.503
- Yes, then we have to wait
another couple of years

01:13:32.504 --> 01:13:34.641
for the next round.

01:13:36.639 --> 01:13:38.909
No, another two years,
I'm saying...

01:13:42.574 --> 01:13:44.204
But still, it doesn't matter.

01:13:44.205 --> 01:13:45.576
You'll be working harder.

01:13:48.459 --> 01:13:50.037
No, but independent of that,

01:13:50.038 --> 01:13:54.505
I think you'll know the truth.

01:13:54.506 --> 01:13:56.238
Yes, yes, no.

01:13:56.239 --> 01:13:58.707
- And that's
the important thing.

01:13:59.706 --> 01:14:02.974
No, you're right.
Yes, of course.

01:14:05.971 --> 01:14:07.760
- Coffee
is a very serious business

01:14:08.039 --> 01:14:10.171
in the life of a theorist.

01:14:10.172 --> 01:14:12.304
It's not like physics research,

01:14:12.305 --> 01:14:14.172
where you can wait for 30 years

01:14:14.173 --> 01:14:18.805
before you know
if you are right.

01:14:18.806 --> 01:14:22.739
Within a few minutes,
it pays off.

01:14:22.740 --> 01:14:26.041
If you succeed, it's great.

01:14:27.040 --> 01:14:29.972
If you fail,
you get to try another one

01:14:29.973 --> 01:14:31.906
in another minute.

01:14:31.907 --> 01:14:33.840
In particle physics,

01:14:33.842 --> 01:14:37.838
you construct
a theory 20 years ago,

01:14:37.840 --> 01:14:39.840
and it may take that long

01:14:39.841 --> 01:14:42.872
before you know
if you're on the right track.

01:14:42.874 --> 01:14:45.373
Jumping from failure to failure

01:14:45.374 --> 01:14:47.805
with undiminished enthusiasm

01:14:47.806 --> 01:14:51.972
is the big secret to success.

01:14:51.973 --> 01:14:58.307
- Well, the hint
that the Higgs was 140 GeV

01:14:58.308 --> 01:15:01.039
has disappeared.

01:15:01.040 --> 01:15:06.174
All of the new data
that just came in

01:15:06.175 --> 01:15:08.674
didn't make the peak bigger.

01:15:08.675 --> 01:15:11.474
It sort of filled in the gaps.

01:15:11.475 --> 01:15:15.640
And now the peak
doesn't look very good.

01:15:15.641 --> 01:15:19.841
In fact, the belief
is that it's gone away

01:15:19.842 --> 01:15:25.175
and that the Higgs
can't be 140 GeV.

01:15:25.176 --> 01:15:28.475
In order for us to believe
that we've discovered it,

01:15:28.476 --> 01:15:30.175
that peak needs to be big

01:15:30.175 --> 01:15:33.408
and basically keep growing
as the data comes in.

01:15:33.409 --> 01:15:36.241
It's a statistical thing.

01:15:36.242 --> 01:15:38.675
We call it the Greek letter
"sigma."

01:15:38.676 --> 01:15:42.008
If you reach a height
of 5 sigma,

01:15:42.009 --> 01:15:45.407
that's when you know
that you've seen something.

01:15:45.408 --> 01:15:48.875
And the probability that
that just happens by accident

01:15:48.876 --> 01:15:52.379
is 1 in 31/2 million.

01:15:55.375 --> 01:15:59.241
But the Higgs, it's not at 140,

01:15:59.242 --> 01:16:01.642
which is a bit of a relief,

01:16:01.643 --> 01:16:06.309
because there's still hope
it might be down around 115.

01:16:06.310 --> 01:16:07.910
We like 115,

01:16:07.911 --> 01:16:10.309
because if the Higgs
is that light,

01:16:10.310 --> 01:16:13.308
the theory says
there has to be new particles,

01:16:13.309 --> 01:16:15.208
like supersymmetry,

01:16:15.209 --> 01:16:19.876
otherwise the universe
is unstable.

01:16:19.877 --> 01:16:22.679
It wouldn't have survived
this long.

01:16:24.976 --> 01:16:29.041
- This is one of the one
of the few truly perfect

01:16:29.042 --> 01:16:30.676
academic institutions
in the world.

01:16:30.677 --> 01:16:32.977
I mean, there's no excuse...

01:16:32.978 --> 01:16:34.676
no excuse at all...

01:16:34.677 --> 01:16:39.210
not to think and work

01:16:39.211 --> 01:16:40.810
and get things done.

01:16:40.810 --> 01:16:42.143
That's its only problem.

01:16:42.144 --> 01:16:43.743
There's no excuse at all
not to think

01:16:43.744 --> 01:16:45.643
and work and get things done.

01:16:45.644 --> 01:16:47.877
You can't blame it on anything
if it doesn't work.

01:16:47.878 --> 01:16:51.810
- Okay, supersymmetry
versus multiverse.

01:16:51.811 --> 01:16:54.044
Oh, boy.

01:16:57.211 --> 01:16:58.645
All right.

01:16:58.645 --> 01:17:00.144
That's, uh...

01:17:00.145 --> 01:17:01.543
If we're going to start
doing that,

01:17:01.544 --> 01:17:03.680
this is going to be interesting.

01:17:05.678 --> 01:17:08.511
We have been anticipating
that whatever happens

01:17:08.512 --> 01:17:10.845
