01:28:48.435 --> 01:28:49.835
Congratulations.

01:28:49.836 --> 01:28:52.570
Thank you. Thank you.

01:29:24.037 --> 01:29:31.002
- I did feel a sense of pride
when the Higgs was announced,

01:29:31.003 --> 01:29:34.869
but I felt a sense of pride
for humanity,

01:29:34.870 --> 01:29:38.835
that, you know, we little people
on a little planet

01:29:38.836 --> 01:29:40.702
with tiny brains

01:29:40.703 --> 01:29:43.936
can go so deep
and understand what happens.

01:29:43.937 --> 01:29:47.404
Now we're talking
about subnuclear distances

01:29:47.405 --> 01:29:50.370
a thousand times smaller
than an atomic nucleus.

01:29:50.371 --> 01:29:52.870
Nevertheless,
we can get things right,

01:29:52.870 --> 01:29:56.175
and just the power
of the human mind.

01:29:59.171 --> 01:30:03.871
It's astonishing that there are
any laws of nature at all,

01:30:03.872 --> 01:30:07.939
that they're describable
by mathematics,

01:30:07.940 --> 01:30:13.071
that mathematics is a tool
that humans can understand,

01:30:13.072 --> 01:30:17.203
that the laws of nature
can be written on a page.

01:30:17.204 --> 01:30:20.840
It's the greatest
of all mysteries.

01:30:23.838 --> 01:30:30.604
There is a strong sense that we
are hearing nature talk to us.

01:30:30.605 --> 01:30:32.871
Turns out, the Higgs mass

01:30:32.872 --> 01:30:35.371
is about as interesting
as it could be.

01:30:35.372 --> 01:30:38.204
It's sort of in no man's land.

01:30:38.205 --> 01:30:40.372
It doesn't prefer symmetries,

01:30:40.373 --> 01:30:42.238
and it doesn't prefer
multiverse,

01:30:42.239 --> 01:30:43.940
but it's right in the middle.

01:30:43.940 --> 01:30:47.838
The data is puzzling enough

01:30:47.838 --> 01:30:52.705
that it hasn't excluded
any of the theories

01:30:52.706 --> 01:30:54.205
I was involved with,

01:30:54.206 --> 01:30:56.439
but it hasn't
confirmed them either.

01:30:56.440 --> 01:31:00.705
But until we look at detailed
properties of the Higgs,

01:31:00.706 --> 01:31:04.005
and until we have
the high-energy version

01:31:04.006 --> 01:31:07.172
of the LHC in a couple of years,

01:31:07.173 --> 01:31:10.674
we will not be able
to make a stronger statement.

01:31:13.341 --> 01:31:15.204
- The most important,
first lesson

01:31:15.205 --> 01:31:17.272
of the discovery of the Higgs

01:31:17.273 --> 01:31:20.105
is that physics works.

01:31:20.106 --> 01:31:21.774
The Higgs, on the one hand,

01:31:21.775 --> 01:31:24.074
completes the most successful
scientific theory

01:31:24.075 --> 01:31:25.408
we've ever had,

01:31:25.409 --> 01:31:27.240
on the other hand,
opens the door

01:31:27.241 --> 01:31:32.607
to some very major paradoxes
that we now must address.

01:31:32.608 --> 01:31:35.506
We're at a fork in the road,
and the LHC

01:31:35.507 --> 01:31:38.105
is steadfastly refusing
to push us

01:31:38.106 --> 01:31:40.242
in one direction or the other:

01:31:40.243 --> 01:31:42.007
the multiverse on the one side,

01:31:42.008 --> 01:31:46.608
and some beautiful symmetry
on the other side.

01:31:46.608 --> 01:31:50.415
It's cranking up the suspense
as much as it possibly can.

01:31:56.174 --> 01:31:58.541
- Before the LHC started,
we would always say,

01:31:58.542 --> 01:32:00.908
"New physics
is just around the corner."

01:32:00.909 --> 01:32:02.241
And now we're kind of like,

01:32:02.242 --> 01:32:03.942
"New physics
is still out there."

01:32:03.943 --> 01:32:07.174
And, for one,
I'm not discouraged by this,

01:32:07.175 --> 01:32:10.776
by any means, because we know

01:32:10.777 --> 01:32:12.778
that new physics
has to be out there.

01:32:14.776 --> 01:32:18.443
The next step is,
the LHC goes into a shutdown,

01:32:18.444 --> 01:32:22.108
stays off for two years
for improvements and upgrades,

01:32:22.109 --> 01:32:25.208
and when it returns, it's
going to be twice the energy.

01:32:25.209 --> 01:32:29.013
And for sure,
my vote's for supersymmetry.

01:32:33.009 --> 01:32:34.841
Jesus.

01:32:34.842 --> 01:32:36.108
That was exciting.

01:32:37.376 --> 01:32:39.876
If this is true,

01:32:39.877 --> 01:32:43.708
the Higgs is about 125 GeV,

01:32:43.709 --> 01:32:47.508
and that means...

01:32:47.509 --> 01:32:52.008
um, yeah, actually
almost all of my models

01:32:52.009 --> 01:32:53.709
are ruled out,

01:32:53.710 --> 01:32:56.610
which...
all the supersymmetry models,

01:32:56.611 --> 01:32:59.710
which is pretty cool.

01:32:59.711 --> 01:33:02.510
I mean, supersymmetry
could still be true,

01:33:02.511 --> 01:33:07.110
but it would have to be a very
strange version of the theory.

01:33:07.110 --> 01:33:09.510
And if it's the multiverse...

01:33:09.511 --> 01:33:13.210
well, other universes
would be amazing, of course,

01:33:13.211 --> 01:33:18.844
but it could also mean no
other new particles discovered,

01:33:18.845 --> 01:33:22.376
and then
a Higgs with a mass of 125

01:33:22.377 --> 01:33:27.244
is right at a critical point
for the fate of our universe.

01:33:27.245 --> 01:33:29.744
Without any other new particles,

01:33:29.744 --> 01:33:31.876
that Higgs is unstable.

01:33:31.877 --> 01:33:33.945
It's temporary.

01:33:33.946 --> 01:33:36.912
And since the Higgs
holds everything together,

01:33:37.911 --> 01:33:41.848
if the Higgs goes,
everything goes.

01:33:44.846 --> 01:33:46.511
It's amazing that the Higgs,

01:33:46.512 --> 01:33:48.711
the center
of the Standard Model,

01:33:48.712 --> 01:33:50.510
the thing we've all
been looking for,

01:33:50.511 --> 01:33:53.917
could actually also be the thing
that destroys everything.

01:33:58.913 --> 01:34:02.284
The creator and the destroyer.

01:34:07.280 --> 01:34:10.110
But we could discover
new particles,

01:34:10.111 --> 01:34:12.716
and then none of that
would be true.

01:34:14.714 --> 01:34:17.766
And anyway,
we have something to do.

01:34:36.748 --> 01:34:41.179
<i>- There is a very nice sentence
in the Divine Comedy by Dante</i>

01:34:41.180 --> 01:34:44.779
<i>who says, "Nati
non fummo a viver come bruti,</i>

01:34:44.780 --> 01:34:48.681
<i>ma per seguir
virtute e canoscenza,"</i>

01:34:48.682 --> 01:34:51.014
which means, "We were not born

01:34:51.015 --> 01:34:52.512
"to live as animals,

01:34:52.513 --> 01:34:56.214
but to pursue knowledge
and virtue."

01:34:56.215 --> 01:34:58.913
So science and knowledge
are very important,

01:34:58.914 --> 01:35:02.248
like art is very important.

01:35:02.249 --> 01:35:05.246
It's a need of mankind.

01:35:05.247 --> 01:35:07.782
I just saw, two weeks ago,

01:35:07.783 --> 01:35:10.181
Werner Herzog talking about

01:35:10.182 --> 01:35:13.180
and then screening
his new movie.

01:35:13.181 --> 01:35:14.781
But it was about
these incredible caves

01:35:14.782 --> 01:35:17.014
that they discovered
a few years ago in France.

01:35:17.015 --> 01:35:18.513
Stunningly beautiful.

01:35:18.514 --> 01:35:21.715
Gorgeously drawn horses, bison,

01:35:21.716 --> 01:35:24.448
rhinoceros, lions,

01:35:24.449 --> 01:35:26.582
because, 40,000 years ago,

01:35:26.583 --> 01:35:28.416
this is what was going on there.

01:35:45.417 --> 01:35:50.115
- In exploration...
- and science is exploration...

01:35:50.116 --> 01:35:52.785
there needs to be
the set of people

01:35:53.784 --> 01:35:55.515
who have no rules,

01:35:55.516 --> 01:35:58.784
and they are going
into the frontier

01:35:59.783 --> 01:36:03.249
and come back
with the strange animals

01:36:03.250 --> 01:36:06.616
and the interesting rocks
and the amazing pictures,

01:36:06.617 --> 01:36:09.415
and to show us what's out there,

01:36:09.416 --> 01:36:11.624
discover something.

01:36:17.618 --> 01:36:20.083
Why do humans do science?

01:36:20.084 --> 01:36:22.784
Why do they do art?

01:36:22.785 --> 01:36:28.084
The things that are least
important for our survival

01:36:28.085 --> 01:36:30.743
are the very things
that make us human.

